(261, 17, 1, '', '2014-12-24 04:03:02', 307, 22422, '7535d58f5205537d36e24691ed3d1bb6174b70e1', '{"id":17,"asset_id":"111","title":"How to protect yourself online","alias":"how-to-protect-yourself-online","introtext":"<p><img src=\\"images\\/perzo-safelock-900-80-300x168.jpg\\" alt=\\"\\" \\/><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>There\\u2019s little question that hardware and software developers have become much better at delivering secure products.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Windows vulnerabilities are rarer, most software auto-patches these days and curated app stores can help users steer away from the shonkier sources of apps.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>But as the software has evolved, so have the net nasties. Mobiles, social networking, traffic direction systems and critical infrastructure have become common targets. Targeted breaches of online databases have been a large theme in the past year \\u2013 that\\u2019s not us getting hacked, but the people to whom we trust our data.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>And we have learnt that we have more than just criminals we have to worry about: governments and business have proven more than willing to snoop on our every online activity.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>So what can you do? We\\u2019ve put together a quick list of the major current threats and how to best avoid them.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Windows XP<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>On April 8, Microsoft called it quits on Windows XP and Office 2003. Even though both still enjoy a significant user base, there will be no more patches or updates for the operating system or office suite. That makes them uniquely vulnerable, and if you\\u2019re still using XP, it\\u2019s definitely time to think about upgrading.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u00a0<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>Malware<\\/h3>\\r\\n<h4>The Problem<\\/h4>\\r\\n<p>For most users, malware remains the most pressing online threat. The term is short for malicious software, and it covers viruses, worms, trojans, spyware, ransomware and any other software that exists to ruin your day. A lot of people also use the terms to describe potentially unwanted software (PUP), which is the unwanted crud like browser toolbars and other adware that so often gets delivered with \\u201cfree\\u201d and sometimes with paid software.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Malware is nearly always installed by the user, typically by executing a script or opening an application that they shouldn\\u2019t have. Trojan horses account for some 70% of malware infections, and the traditional means of delivering malware is still around: downloads from dodgy sites and social engineering attacks (where the user is tricked into opening a file they shouldn\\u2019t) are prominent.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The effects of malware vary wildly, but the overwhelming trend in the last few years has been less \\u201cdestroy everything\\u201d and more \\u201clet\\u2019s steal or extort money from the user.\\u201d According to Sophos\\u2019 Security Threat Report 2014, we\\u2019ve seen a much greater emphasis on compromising financial records and information, on using infected computers for BitCoin mining, and on ransomware, where the documents on infected computers are encrypted with the promise of decryption only if the user pays a ransom.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>And then there are mobile viruses, which primarily affect Android because of its more open architecture. In the first quarter of 2014 alone, the number of mobile banking trojans almost doubled, with some high profile attacks like Faketoken targeting increasingly prominent mobile wallet systems.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h4>\\u00a0The solution<\\/h4>\\r\\n<p>Anti-malware software is still your first line of defense against these attacks \\u2013 although now you have to be cognisant of the need to cover multiple platforms.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>For Windows, it looks very much like third-party anti-virus solutions are still the go. Although Microsoft provides Windows Security Essentials for free for Windows 7, and integrates it into Windows Defender on Windows 8, its protection remains disappointing.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>In its August 2014 anti-virus tests, AV-Test found that Security Essentials picked up just 77% of 0-day and new viruses \\u2013 where most of its competition scored in the 97-100% range.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>SecurityEssentials Android does not come with an integrated anti-malware solution at all \\u2013 but there are many free solutions and commercial available. Among the solutions that scored 100% in AV-Test\\u2019s benchmarks were BitDefender Mobile Security, Bullguard Mobile Security, ESET Mobile Security, Trend Micro Mobile Security and Norton Mobile Security.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Aside from having a software solution in place, all that you can really do is take care with what you run on your computing platforms.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The use of curated app stores is a good start. Although the Google Play store, for example, has been infiltrated by viruses a few times, infected files rarely stay up for long, and setting your Android to only support apps from the official store is good policy (the control is found under Security\\u2013&gt;Unknown sources in the Android settings).<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>On Windows 8 you can use the Windows Store, which is a good place to get \\u201csafe\\u201d apps \\u2013 or at least non-desktop ones. For now, the Windows Store still redirects you off-site for any Desktop apps \\u2013 which is to say, the vast majority of existing apps \\u2013 and many desktop apps don\\u2019t even bother listing on the Windows Store.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>A blog post on Microsoft\\u2019s site indicated that when Windows 10 comes out it will include support for Desktop apps in the Windows Store, but that blog post has since been deleted so at the time of writing nothing was confirmed.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u00a0<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>Passwords and hacking<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p><a href=\\"http:\\/\\/media.apcmag.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/sites\\/20\\/2014\\/11\\/GooglePlay.jpg\\"><img class=\\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-356793\\" src=\\"http:\\/\\/media.apcmag.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/sites\\/20\\/2014\\/11\\/GooglePlay-640x271.jpg\\" alt=\\"GooglePlay\\" \\/><\\/a><\\/p>\\r\\n<h4>The Problem<\\/h4>\\r\\n<p>Nary a week goes by now without news that somebody\\u2019s phone, cloud storage, web site, Facebook, Instagram or twitter account has been \\u201chacked.\\u201d It has become so common that it\\u2019s not even really news anymore.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Contrary to what you see on TV and in the movies, however, the vast majority of these hacks are not the product of some technical wizardry. Instead, they\\u2019re most commonly the product of password hacks, scams, spyware and social engineering. Actual technical hacks are quite rare these days \\u2013 everything is pretty much firewall protected by default, and software and hardware developers having become much better at securing their products. But what they can\\u2019t do is protect users against letting other people know their password and private information that might allow them to bypass online security checks.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h4>The solution<\\/h4>\\r\\n<p>The easy answer is \\u201cgood passwords\\u201d \\u2013 which is to say random strings of alphanumeric characters. At least eight characters long, including upper and lower case and numbers. Of course, given that each of us has roughly two million different passwords we have to remember (and using the same password for everything is just bad), that\\u2019s not all that practical.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>However, a password manager <em>is<\\/em> practical. Our current top pick is LastPass (<span class=\\"skimlinks-unlinked\\">lastpass.com<\\/span>). LastPass is free (for the basic version), easy to use, remembers your passwords for both apps and Web sites, is multi-platform, includes cloud syncing and backup and will automatically generate and store passwords for you. You only need to remember the master password for LastPass.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>It primarily works as an add-on for your Web browser, and will import your saved browser passwords when you install it. Afterwards, you can click on the LastPass browser button to access its features \\u2013 you can set it to automatically log you into sites with saved passwords, you can use the password generator, auto fill out forms (including card numbers) or configure your identity.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>LastPass is certainly not the only password manager out there. If you don\\u2019t like it, you can also try KeePass (<span class=\\"skimlinks-unlinked\\">keepass.com<\\/span>), eWallet (<span class=\\"skimlinks-unlinked\\">www.iliumsoft.com\\/ewallet<\\/span>), DashLane (<span class=\\"skimlinks-unlinked\\">www.dashlane.com<\\/span>), RoboForm (<span class=\\"skimlinks-unlinked\\">www.roboform.com<\\/span>) and F-Secure Key (<a class=\\"skimlinks-unlinked\\" title=\\"\\" href=\\"http:\\/\\/www.f-secure.com\\/\\" data-skimwords-word=\\"www.f-secure.com\\" data-skim-creative=\\"500005\\"><span style=\\"text-decoration: underline;\\"><span style=\\"color: #009fe4;\\">www.f-secure.com<\\/span><\\/span><\\/a>). If you purchase a suite (see page ^), many now come bundled with password managers built in, or have them available as separate downloads. Symantec, BitDefender and F-Secure have particularly solid implementations.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h4>How they got hacked<\\/h4>\\r\\n<p>The celebrity hacking scandal of August and September was one of the most-publicised instances of privacy invasion in recent memory. Over a hundred celebrities had their cloud phone backups hacked and their private photo and video collections posted online.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>It\\u2019s not 100% clear how the celebrity phone accounts were hacked, but according to Apple it wasn\\u2019t because of a technical vulnerability in the iCloud services. Instead, the hacker(s) in question accessed the iCloud phone backups through good old password hackery. The passwords were obtained with either through a phishing attack, or, more likely through brute force attacks.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The latter is surprisingly simple to accomplish, and does not require any significant technical knowledge on the part of the hacker. Instead, existing scripting tools are used to make a \\u201cdictionary attack\\u201d against an account. That is, simply trying out a bunch of common words and phrases and seeing if one works. An automated tool can try hundreds or thousands every hour.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>If nothing else, the incident demonstrates the need for good passwords. Regular words and phrases don\\u2019t cut it anymore.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><a href=\\"http:\\/\\/media.apcmag.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/sites\\/20\\/2014\\/11\\/LastPass.jpg\\"><img class=\\"alignleft wp-image-356796 size-medium\\" src=\\"http:\\/\\/media.apcmag.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/sites\\/20\\/2014\\/11\\/LastPass-300x193.jpg\\" alt=\\"LastPass\\" \\/><\\/a><\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>Web tracking<\\/h3>\\r\\n<h4>The problem<\\/h4>\\r\\n<p>Facebook is everywhere. So is DoubleClick online advertising. Disqus, too. And thanks to tracking cookies, both these organisations, and many others like them, have a tremendous ability to track your online activity.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Tracking cookies allow them to know when you visit a web site with one of their ads or widgets embedded. By monitoring your activity, they can build a pretty complete picture of who you are and what you like \\u2013 all the better to deliver targeted advertising.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>If you\\u2019d rather not be so tracked, however, there are some remediation tools available to you. Of course, you can switch off all cookies \\u2013 but that can be pretty inconvenient. After all, cookies can be useful for storing your site preferences, for example, and are pretty crucial in online shopping.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h4>The solution<\\/h4>\\r\\n<p>Disconnect (<span class=\\"skimlinks-unlinked\\">disconnect.me<\\/span>) is far and away our current favourite solution for dealing with tracking cookies. It\\u2019s available as an add-on for Chrome, Safari, Firefox and Opera, and it filters out a tremendous amount of third-party content. When you visit a site that has a Facebook or other social networking widget embedded or calls out to ad services or web analytics, Disconnect automatically blocks them. You can whitelist a site if you want to (in case you actually do want to use the Facebook Like button), but by default anything that might be used to track you is zapped.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>You should also learn to use and love private browsing. Internet Explorer, Chrome, Opera and Firefox all have privacy modes. In Chrome it\\u2019s Incognito; in Firefox and Opera it\\u2019s Private Window; in IE it\\u2019s InPrivate Browsing. With these tools, you open a new private\\/incognito tab or window and any sites you open in the tab or window are effectively sandboxed. They can\\u2019t talk to your existing cookies, and when you end the private\\/incognito session all cookies created during it are deleted. It effectively foils attempts to track you using cookies. Just between us chickens, it\\u2019s also a handy way to get around sites that limit visitations, such as sites that only allow you to view X articles per month.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h4>Spam<\\/h4>\\r\\n<p>We didn\\u2019t include spam on the list because, well, it\\u2019s not really the problem it used to be. Sure, there\\u2019s still plenty of it, but between web-based filtering and automatic filtering in Outlook\\/Thunderbird, it not really the issue that it once was.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>Identity theft, phishing and scams<\\/h3>\\r\\n<h4>The Problem<\\/h4>\\r\\n<p>While technical defenses have improved in recent years, the sophistication of social engineering attacks has also increased significantly. The Symantec 2014 Internet Security Threat Report revealed that identity theft using social networking is a growing problem, with criminals using Facebook profiles to create or acquire credit card information. What\\u2019s more, they\\u2019re using it to make more sophisticated phishing attacks and scams. According to Symantec, the number of target \\u201cspear-phishing\\u201d attacks grew by 91% in 2013.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The classical phishing attack for example, is an urgent email from your \\u201cbank\\u201d that promises dire consequences if you don\\u2019t click on a link and enter your Net Banking password. Users have become savvy to that, and banks better protected with two-factor authentication, so new techniques have been employed. In one spear-phishing example, you might get an email that appears to be from someone you know like your boss \\u2013 information gleaned from your Facebook or Linked-in profile \\u2013 that requests that you urgently open a malware-infected file. The malware is then used to spy on your system and gather personal financial information.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h4>The Solution<\\/h4>\\r\\n<p>Security suites are your best <em>technical<\\/em> solution. The best ones will include identity theft protection tools and complex mail filters that can pick out scams and remove malware from email attachments.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Outside of suites, it\\u2019s really just a matter of eternal vigilance. Be wary of executable email attachments. Assume anybody who asks for personal information is a scam artist. Don\\u2019t overshare on social networks. Teach your kids and significant others to assume that people you speak to and meet online are not to be trusted by default.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h4>Megahacks<\\/h4>\\r\\n<p>Some very large organisations have had their customer databases hacked in the past year, and millions of personal financial records compromised. Typically using SQL injection techniques, hackers have acquired hundreds of millions of financial records and email addresses from major companies. If a company you\\u2019ve entrusted with your financial data gets hacked, the best thing you can do is contact your financial institution, which can provide advice on what your next move should be, if any. The major banks have become quite adept at dealing with this of late!<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>The Snoops<\\/h3>\\r\\n<h4>The Problem<\\/h4>\\r\\n<p>You are being watched. The government has a secret system \\u2014a machine\\u2014 that spies on you every hour of every day.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>OK, not really, but thanks to Edward Snowden, we do know that the surveillance state is real and that internet monitoring is happening on a massive scale. Once again, spy agencies in Australia are pushing for regulations to force ISPs to monitor and record all the sites we visit, and it\\u2019s also well known that many companies such as Google are keeping massive archives of our online activity for their own purposes.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h4>The Solution<\\/h4>\\r\\n<p>If that\\u2019s something you\\u2019re uncomfortable with, then there are various tools you can use to foil attempts to monitor your activity and intercept your data. We don\\u2019t have space here to go into them all in depth, but here are our top picks for maximum data privacy.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Encrypted text chat: For the PC we like <a href=\\"http:\\/\\/www.chatcrypt.com\\/\\"><span style=\\"text-decoration: underline;\\"><span style=\\"color: #009fe4;\\">ChatCrypt<\\/span><\\/span><\\/a> \\u2013 it\\u2019s a little rough for one-to-one communications, but for encrypted group chat it works well. On Android phones we like <a href=\\"http:\\/\\/whispersystems.org\\/\\"><span style=\\"text-decoration: underline;\\"><span style=\\"color: #009fe4;\\">TextSecure<\\/span><\\/span><\\/a>, which looks and works a lot like SMS, except it\\u2019s both encrypted and its free apart from miniscule data charges.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><a href=\\"http:\\/\\/media.apcmag.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/sites\\/20\\/2014\\/11\\/RedPhone.png\\"><img class=\\"alignright wp-image-356799 size-medium\\" src=\\"http:\\/\\/media.apcmag.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/sites\\/20\\/2014\\/11\\/RedPhone-180x300.png\\" alt=\\"RedPhone\\" \\/><\\/a><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Encrypted voice chat: <a href=\\"http:\\/\\/jitsi.org\\/\\"><span style=\\"text-decoration: underline;\\"><span style=\\"color: #009fe4;\\">Jitsi<\\/span><\\/span><\\/a> for Windows and <a href=\\"http:\\/\\/whispersystems.org\\/\\"><span style=\\"text-decoration: underline;\\"><span style=\\"color: #009fe4;\\">RedPhone<\\/span><\\/span><\\/a> for Android provide encrypted voice chat. Jitsi works, in practice, a lot like Skype \\u2013 except that it\\u2019s not controlled by Microsoft and calls can be encrypted. RedPhone integrates smoothly into your Android phone, and you can make calls to other RedPhone users quite transparently \\u2013 it\\u2019s just like making a regular phone call.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Encrypted email: <a href=\\"http:\\/\\/www.gpg4win.org\\/\\"><span style=\\"text-decoration: underline;\\"><span style=\\"color: #009fe4;\\">Gpg4win<\\/span><\\/span><\\/a> is your go-to solution for email encryption \\u2013 or encryption of any other text-based correspondence, really. You\\u2019ll have to do a little reading to get up to speed on using it.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Untraceable browsing: the <a href=\\"http:\\/\\/www.torproject.org\\/\\"><span style=\\"text-decoration: underline;\\"><span style=\\"color: #009fe4;\\">TOR browser<\\/span><\\/span><\\/a>. With TOR, all your connections are routed through several other PCs, obscuring the connection between you and site you\\u2019re visiting and making your IP address effectively untraceable. It\\u2019s the ultimate in privacy.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><a href=\\"http:\\/\\/media.apcmag.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/sites\\/20\\/2014\\/11\\/Disconnect.jpg\\"><img class=\\"alignleft wp-image-356790 size-medium\\" src=\\"http:\\/\\/media.apcmag.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/sites\\/20\\/2014\\/11\\/Disconnect-173x300.jpg\\" alt=\\"Disconnect\\" \\/><\\/a><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>If TOR is a little heavy handed for you, you can also use a VPN service, of which there are dozens. StrongVPN (<span class=\\"skimlinks-unlinked\\">strongvpn.com<\\/span>), IPVanish (<span class=\\"skimlinks-unlinked\\">ipvanish.com<\\/span>), VyprVPN (<span class=\\"skimlinks-unlinked\\">vyprvpn.com<\\/span>), HideMyAss (<span class=\\"skimlinks-unlinked\\">hidemyass.com<\\/span>) and many other options are available to you.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h4>The RSA Backdoor<\\/h4>\\r\\n<p>One of the many programs revealed during the Edward Snowden leaks was Bullrun, a clandestine NSA operation devoted to the decryption of private and governmental communication using custom-made hardware along with technical backdoors.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Perhaps the most shocking revelation was that RSA, the makers of one of the world\\u2019s most widely used encryption algorithms, accepted $10 million US dollars from the NSA to use as default the Dual_EC_DRBG random number generator in its BSafe toolkit. Dual_EC_DRBG had a known deficiency that allowed the NSA to more easily crack encryption keys. It was later revealed that this payment was part of a larger program that was designed to infiltrate and control cryptographic standards agencies and organisations, including the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Following the revelations in 2013, RSA stopped using Dual_EC_DRBG as the default and recommended that existing users switch to one of the other random number generators available. The incident has put a big black mark on many closed source encryption providers, and groups like OpenSSL and the FreeBSD developers have stopped using many hardware random number generators for fear that they too may have been compromised.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>{jumi [*3] [Nathan Taylor] [http:\\/\\/apcmag.com\\/how-to-protect-yourself-online.htm]}<\\/p>","fulltext":"","state":1,"catid":"12","created":"2014-12-01 04:49:00","created_by":"307","created_by_alias":"","modified":"2014-12-24 04:03:02","modified_by":"307","checked_out":"307","checked_out_time":"2014-12-24 04:02:55","publish_up":"2014-12-23 04:49:16","publish_down":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","images":"{\\"image_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"float_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_caption\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext\\":\\"\\",\\"float_fulltext\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext_caption\\":\\"\\"}","urls":"{\\"urla\\":false,\\"urlatext\\":\\"\\",\\"targeta\\":\\"\\",\\"urlb\\":false,\\"urlbtext\\":\\"\\",\\"targetb\\":\\"\\",\\"urlc\\":false,\\"urlctext\\":\\"\\",\\"targetc\\":\\"\\"}","attribs":"{\\"show_title\\":\\"\\",\\"link_titles\\":\\"\\",\\"show_tags\\":\\"\\",\\"show_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"info_block_position\\":\\"\\",\\"show_category\\":\\"\\",\\"link_category\\":\\"\\",\\"show_parent_category\\":\\"\\",\\"link_parent_category\\":\\"\\",\\"show_author\\":\\"\\",\\"link_author\\":\\"\\",\\"show_create_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_modify_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_publish_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_item_navigation\\":\\"\\",\\"show_icons\\":\\"\\",\\"show_print_icon\\":\\"\\",\\"show_email_icon\\":\\"\\",\\"show_vote\\":\\"\\",\\"show_hits\\":\\"\\",\\"show_noauth\\":\\"\\",\\"urls_position\\":\\"\\",\\"alternative_readmore\\":\\"\\",\\"article_layout\\":\\"\\",\\"show_publishing_options\\":\\"\\",\\"show_article_options\\":\\"\\",\\"show_urls_images_backend\\":\\"\\",\\"show_urls_images_frontend\\":\\"\\"}","version":6,"ordering":"5","metakey":"","metadesc":"","access":"1","hits":"3","metadata":"{\\"robots\\":\\"\\",\\"author\\":\\"\\",\\"rights\\":\\"\\",\\"xreference\\":\\"\\"}","featured":"0","language":"*","xreference":""}', 0),
(262, 21, 1, '', '2014-12-24 04:03:35', 307, 7748, 'e42d2eeddd3f4b5cc2ba0112caef8ce4fcec6df0', '{"id":21,"asset_id":"115","title":"Telco customers \\u2018ripped off\\u2019 on fees","alias":"telco-customers-ripped-off-on-fees","introtext":"<p><img src=\\"http:\\/\\/resources1.news.com.au\\/images\\/2014\\/08\\/20\\/1227030\\/592697-4cddffa2-2802-11e4-a134-cf54b9daa685.jpg\\" alt=\\"Telstra\\u2019s financial statement indicated it collected $272 million for \\u201clate fees and othe\\" width=\\"302\\" height=\\"170\\" \\/> <!-- \\/\\/ .image-frame --><\\/p>\\r\\n<p class=\\"caption\\"><span class=\\"caption-text\\">Telstra\\u2019s financial statement indicated it collected $272 million for \\u201clate fees and other miscellaneous fees\\u201d in the 2014 financial year.<\\/span> <span class=\\"image-source\\"><em>Source:<\\/em> AFP<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><!-- \\/\\/ .caption --> <!-- \\/\\/ .tabs .js-tabbed --> <!-- \\/\\/ .article-media --><\\/p>\\r\\n<div class=\\"story-intro\\">\\r\\n<p><strong><!-- google_ad_section_start(name=story_introduction, weight=high) --> FIRST they came for the banks \\u2014 now they\\u2019re coming for the telcos. <!-- google_ad_section_end(name=story_introduction) --> <\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/div>\\r\\n<p><!-- \\/\\/ .story-intro --> <!-- google_ad_section_start(name=story_body, weight=high) --><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Telstra customers who have paid late fees could be in for a big payday if a new multi-million dollar class action is successful.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Specialist law firm ACA Lawyers has announced a class action \\u2014 backed by UK litigation funder Harbour Litigation Funding \\u2014 against Telstra\\u2019s late payments fees.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The legal firm also intends to lodge class actions against Optus and Vodafone. Telstra, Optus and Vodafone customers who have paid a late fee within the past six years will be entitled to join the actions.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>ACA Lawyers will argue the fees represent an unlawful penalty because they do not reflect the actual loss to the company caused by the late payment.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The move comes after legal firm Maurice Blackburn initiated Australia\\u2019s biggest ever class action, which seeks compensation for customers of Westpac, St. George, Citibank, BankSA and ANZ over late payment fees.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>ACA Lawyers principal Steven Lewis told news.com.au it was too early to say how many customers might take part in the action. \\u201cKeep in mind Telstra has 16 million mobile services and 7.5 million fixed voice \\u2014 not everyone pays their bill late, but I can guarantee you most people have paid their bill late at least once,\\u201d Mr Lewis said.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Should the action be successful, customers could potentially be eligible for any late fees paid plus interest, minus the actual cost to Telstra as assessed by the court. \\u201cThe thing to note is the people who are slugged with these fees are generally the ones who can least afford it,\\u201d he added.<\\/p>\\r\\n<div class=\\"module image-module module-image-650w366h  id1227030644004\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"module-content\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"image-block image-650w366h\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"image-frame\\"><img src=\\"http:\\/\\/resources0.news.com.au\\/images\\/2014\\/08\\/20\\/1227030\\/644004-ac7880ce-2814-11e4-a134-cf54b9daa685.jpg\\" alt=\\"CEO David Thodey speaking about Telstra''s profit result last week.\\" width=\\"650\\" height=\\"366\\" \\/><\\/div>\\r\\n<!--  \\/\\/ .image-frame -->\\r\\n<p class=\\"caption\\"><span class=\\"caption-text\\">CEO David Thodey speaking about Telstra''s profit result last week.<\\/span> <span class=\\"image-source\\"><em>Source:<\\/em> News Corp Australia<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<!-- \\/\\/ .caption --><\\/div>\\r\\n<!-- \\/\\/ .image-block --><\\/div>\\r\\n<!-- \\/\\/ .module-content --><\\/div>\\r\\n<p><!-- \\/\\/ .module .image-module .module-image-freeform --><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u00a0<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>In a statement, Mr Lewis said the action was about justice for the clients of Australia\\u2019s major telcos. He said if the actual cost of collecting the late fees is anything like the real cost of a bank collecting a late fee then Telstra\\u2019s clients are being \\u201cripped off\\u201d on a massive scale.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u201cLast week Telstra announced a massive profit which is built in part on revenue from late payment fees often collected from families who can least afford it,\\u201d Mr Lewis said.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Telstra\\u2019s financial statement indicated it collected $272 million for \\u201clate fees and other miscellaneous fees\\u201d in the 2014 financial year, according to ACA.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The law firm estimates the telco may have collected a further $500 million in late and other miscellaneous fees since July 2009.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u201cSince 2000 hundreds of thousands of Telstra customers have paid late fees in the mistaken belief Telstra was entitled to charge the fee,\\u201d Mr Lewis added.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u201cBut a recent court decision in relation to credit card fees found that late payment fees charged by banks are unlawful and that clients are entitled to get most of their money back.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u201cWe will argue this is the same for the late payment fees charged by Telstra, Optus and Vodafone.\\u201d<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Telstra currently charges a $15 late fee if the amount outstanding on the bill is $70 or more. Optus charges late fees of $15 if the outstanding amount is between $50 and $100, and $15 plus interest if the amount is over $100. Vodafone charges a flat late fee of $10.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>A Telstra spokeswoman said: \\u201cWe will review the claim when we receive it. We believe our late payment fees are reasonable in light of the costs we incur and we will strongly defend any claim we receive.\\u201d<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>An Optus spokeswoman said: \\u201cOptus has not received any legal claims from ACA Lawyers on late payment fees, but will assess any claims if and when they are made.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u201cOptus believes that its late payment arrangements for customers are fair and well-based.\\u201d<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>A Vodafone spokeswoman said: \\u201cWe regularly review all of our plans, including fees, to ensure they are appropriate.\\u201d<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u00a0<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>{jumi [*3] [FRANK CHUNG] [http:\\/\\/www.news.com.au\\/finance\\/business\\/telstra-optus-vodafone-facing-aca-lawyers-class-action-over-unlawful-late-payment-fees\\/story-fn5lic6c-1227030590301]}<\\/p>","fulltext":"","state":1,"catid":"12","created":"2014-08-20 03:51:00","created_by":"307","created_by_alias":"","modified":"2014-12-24 04:03:35","modified_by":"307","checked_out":"307","checked_out_time":"2014-12-24 04:03:25","publish_up":"2014-12-24 03:51:36","publish_down":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","images":"{\\"image_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"float_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_caption\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext\\":\\"\\",\\"float_fulltext\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext_caption\\":\\"\\"}","urls":"{\\"urla\\":false,\\"urlatext\\":\\"\\",\\"targeta\\":\\"\\",\\"urlb\\":false,\\"urlbtext\\":\\"\\",\\"targetb\\":\\"\\",\\"urlc\\":false,\\"urlctext\\":\\"\\",\\"targetc\\":\\"\\"}","attribs":"{\\"show_title\\":\\"\\",\\"link_titles\\":\\"\\",\\"show_tags\\":\\"\\",\\"show_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"info_block_position\\":\\"\\",\\"show_category\\":\\"\\",\\"link_category\\":\\"\\",\\"show_parent_category\\":\\"\\",\\"link_parent_category\\":\\"\\",\\"show_author\\":\\"\\",\\"link_author\\":\\"\\",\\"show_create_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_modify_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_publish_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_item_navigation\\":\\"\\",\\"show_icons\\":\\"\\",\\"show_print_icon\\":\\"\\",\\"show_email_icon\\":\\"\\",\\"show_vote\\":\\"\\",\\"show_hits\\":\\"\\",\\"show_noauth\\":\\"\\",\\"urls_position\\":\\"\\",\\"alternative_readmore\\":\\"\\",\\"article_layout\\":\\"\\",\\"show_publishing_options\\":\\"\\",\\"show_article_options\\":\\"\\",\\"show_urls_images_backend\\":\\"\\",\\"show_urls_images_frontend\\":\\"\\"}","version":4,"ordering":"2","metakey":"","metadesc":"","access":"1","hits":"2","metadata":"{\\"robots\\":\\"\\",\\"author\\":\\"\\",\\"rights\\":\\"\\",\\"xreference\\":\\"\\"}","featured":"0","language":"*","xreference":""}', 0),
(263, 22, 1, '', '2014-12-24 04:04:12', 307, 12857, 'f83f28d9e48dcfc69f7018d799aa2b22b82fa0fc', '{"id":22,"asset_id":"116","title":"The End of Work emails","alias":"the-end-of-work-emails","introtext":"<p><img src=\\"http:\\/\\/resources0.news.com.au\\/images\\/2014\\/07\\/30\\/1227007\\/716704-c9009f84-1788-11e4-85ab-b94874755dbc.jpg\\" alt=\\"No more emails?\\" width=\\"650\\" height=\\"366\\" \\/> <!-- \\/\\/ .image-frame --><\\/p>\\r\\n<p><!-- \\/\\/ .video .js-tab-content --> <!-- \\/\\/ .tabs .js-tabbed --> <!-- \\/\\/ .article-media --><\\/p>\\r\\n<div class=\\"story-intro\\">\\r\\n<p><strong><!-- google_ad_section_start(name=story_introduction, weight=high) --> This year, each worker using a business email account will send and receive a daily average of 121 mail messages, a 15 per cent increase from 105 per day in 2011, according to The Radicati Group, which tracks email usage. <!-- google_ad_section_end(name=story_introduction) --> <\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/div>\\r\\n<p><!-- \\/\\/ .story-intro --> <!-- google_ad_section_start(name=story_body, weight=high) --><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>In contrast, consumers have been weaning themselves from electronic inboxes and increasingly turning to digital alternatives such as Facebook, Twitter and mobile messaging.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>More email translates to less productivity as workers spend more time weeding their inboxes and puzzling over convoluted exchanges among a hodgepodge of colleagues and managers scattered in various offices -or sometimes just a cubicles away. To exacerbate matters, vital pieces of business information are often corralled in a worker\\u2019s inbox instead of in a database that can be searched by anyone working on the same project.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Dustin Moskovitz is plotting an escape from email.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The 30-year-old entrepreneur has learned a lot about communication since he teamed up with his college roommate Mark Zuckerberg to create Facebook a decade ago, and that knowledge is fuelling an audacious attempt to change the way people connect at work, where the incessant drumbeat of email has become an excruciating annoyance.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Moskovitz is trying to turn that chronic headache into an afterthought with Asana, a San Francisco start-up he runs with former Facebook and Google product manager, Justin Rosenstein.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Asana peddles software that combines the elements of a communal notebook, social network, instant messaging application and online calendar to enable teams of employees to share information and do most of their jobs without relying on email.<\\/p>\\r\\n<div class=\\"module image-module module-image-650w488h  id1227007717815\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"module-content\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"image-block image-650w488h\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"image-frame\\"><img src=\\"http:\\/\\/resources3.news.com.au\\/images\\/2014\\/07\\/30\\/1227007\\/717815-4e772aa8-1788-11e4-85ab-b94874755dbc.jpg\\" alt=\\"Asana co-founders Justin Rosenstein and Dustin Moskovitz have big ambitions.\\" width=\\"650\\" height=\\"488\\" \\/><\\/div>\\r\\n<!--  \\/\\/ .image-frame -->\\r\\n<p class=\\"caption\\"><span class=\\"caption-text\\">Asana co-founders Justin Rosenstein and Dustin Moskovitz have big ambitions.<\\/span> <span class=\\"image-source\\"><em>Source:<\\/em> AP<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<!-- \\/\\/ .caption --><\\/div>\\r\\n<!-- \\/\\/ .image-block --><\\/div>\\r\\n<!-- \\/\\/ .module-content --><\\/div>\\r\\n<p><!-- \\/\\/ .module .image-module .module-image-freeform --><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u00a0<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u201cWe are trying to make all the soul-sucking work that comes with email go away,\\u201d Rosenstein says as Moskovitz nods sitting across from him in a former brewery that serves as Asana\\u2019s headquarters. \\u201cThis came out of a deep, heartfelt pain that Dustin and I were experiencing, along with just about everyone around us.\\u201d<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The misery keeps mounting in the corporate world, which remains an email haven.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>If companies set up communications channels that worked more like social networks, the amount of time workers could devote to other things would increase by about 8 per cent each week, according to estimates from a study by the McKinsey Global Institute. Another 6 per cent of the workweek would be freed up if the shift away from email could unlock more of the so-called \\u201cdark matter\\u201d hidden in individual inboxes, McKinsey estimates.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>These are the problems Asana is trying to solve. Its bare-bones system, free to use for teams of up to 15 workers, is set up so information can be easily seen by anyone authorised by the company. Asana hopes to make money by selling subscriptions to more sophisticated versions of its software that can accommodate larger groups of workers.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Moskovitz began working on what would turn into an early prototype for Asana while he was still at Facebook in late 2007. He had become frustrated with email\\u2019s shortcomings and set out to build a better alternative for managing Facebook\\u2019s projects. Before long, he was spending all his time figuring out how to escape email instead of managing Facebook\\u2019s engineers.<\\/p>\\r\\n<div class=\\"module image-module module-image-650w488h  id1227007719167\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"module-content\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"image-block image-650w488h\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"image-frame\\"><img src=\\"http:\\/\\/resources3.news.com.au\\/images\\/2014\\/07\\/30\\/1227007\\/719167-00be71d0-1789-11e4-85ab-b94874755dbc.jpg\\" alt=\\"Could email be going the way of snail mail?\\" width=\\"650\\" height=\\"488\\" \\/><\\/div>\\r\\n<!--  \\/\\/ .image-frame -->\\r\\n<p class=\\"caption\\"><span class=\\"caption-text\\">Could email be going the way of snail mail?<\\/span> <span class=\\"image-source\\"><em>Source:<\\/em> Supplied<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<!-- \\/\\/ .caption --><\\/div>\\r\\n<!-- \\/\\/ .image-block --><\\/div>\\r\\n<!-- \\/\\/ .module-content --><\\/div>\\r\\n<p><!-- \\/\\/ .module .image-module .module-image-freeform --><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u00a0<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u201cA lot of people thought I was crazy, but from my perspective it was clearly the smartest thing that I could do to make (Facebook) better,\\u201d Moskovitz recalls.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>He finally decided to exit Facebook in late 2008 to start Asana, leaving behind a prototype that Facebook still relies on to manage its projects instead of email.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Moskovitz remains one of Facebook\\u2019s major shareholders with stock worth about $7.46 billion, affording him the luxury to gamble on a start-up that may be fighting a Sisyphean battle.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u201cI am not sure what anyone thinks they will be accomplishing by getting rid of email,\\u201d say Sara Radicati, editor of the Radicati Group. \\u201cIf we didn\\u2019t have email, people would be spending all their time on the phone and other channels of communication. Is that really any better?\\u201d<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>While the Radicati Group foresees consumer email usage continuing to wane during the next four years, the firm predicts the volume of business email will rise another 16 per cent by 2018 to an average of 140 daily emails sent and received by each user.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u201cEmail can\\u2019t be killed completely because it\\u2019s the lowest common denominator in business,\\u201d concedes Stewart Butterfield, who has been trying to sell companies on the merits of another alternative form of corporate communication called Slack. Like Moskovitz, Butterfield is better known for his involvement at another popular technology service: he co-founded Flickr, a photo-sharing site bought by Yahoo Inc. nine years ago.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Without providing specifics, Asana says millions of workers are using its system, primarily the free version. In many cases, Asana customers say they have reduced email usage by as much as 80 per cent, according to Rosenstein.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u201cWe are really reaching peak email,\\u201d Rosenstein says. \\u201cOur customers keep asking: \\u2018Can you replace more and more of my email?\\"\\u2019<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Rapidly growing start-ups such as Airbnb, Uber, Pinterest, Dropbox embraced Asana\\u2019s task-management system early in their corporate lives in hopes of avoiding email addiction as they mature.<\\/p>\\r\\n<div class=\\"module image-module module-image-650w488h  id1227007717890\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"module-content\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"image-block image-650w488h\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"image-frame\\"><img src=\\"http:\\/\\/resources2.news.com.au\\/images\\/2014\\/07\\/30\\/1227007\\/717890-52f2d0f0-1788-11e4-85ab-b94874755dbc.jpg\\" alt=\\"Dustin Moskovitz is also well known as a founder of Facebook.\\" width=\\"650\\" height=\\"488\\" \\/><\\/div>\\r\\n<!--  \\/\\/ .image-frame -->\\r\\n<p class=\\"caption\\"><span class=\\"caption-text\\">Dustin Moskovitz is also well known as a founder of Facebook.<\\/span> <span class=\\"image-source\\"><em>Source:<\\/em> AFP<\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n<!-- \\/\\/ .caption --><\\/div>\\r\\n<!-- \\/\\/ .image-block --><\\/div>\\r\\n<!-- \\/\\/ .module-content --><\\/div>\\r\\n<p><!-- \\/\\/ .module .image-module .module-image-freeform --><\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u00a0<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>And Asana isn\\u2019t alone in its quest to eradicate email. Other online services, built especially for business purposes by companies such as Jive Software and Microsoft\\u2019s Yammer, are on a similar mission.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Despite these efforts, email remains pervasive. For instance, Pinterest product manager Michael Yamartino says he still sifts through 200 to 300 emails each day, with 70 per cent of the traffic coming from co-workers. Even after internal meetings, Pinterest still relies on mass emails to let everyone know what is going on.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u201cAsana is better for tracking tasks, but email still has an important place,\\u201d Yamartino says.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Two of Asana\\u2019s own employees, Emily Kramer and Jim Renaud, wanted to prove it\\u2019s possible to survive without email so they vowed to avoid checking their company and personal inboxes for all of April.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>It was the longest stretch that Kramer, 30, had gone without checking her email since she was in the sixth grade when she opened her first account on AOL. Renaud, 39, hadn\\u2019t lived without email since he enrolled in college 20 years ago.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Kramer stayed out of her email, even though she kept fretting about what she might miss at work and had to deal with complaints from friends about the inconvenience of finding other ways to keep her in the loop about a bachelorette party they were planning. She also found herself dealing with lengthier mobile messages that read like email.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u201cA co-worker had told me, \\u2018I think it would be easier to go without oxygen than email,\\u201d Kramer says. \\u201cI definitely don\\u2019t think that\\u2019s true any longer.\\u201d<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Renaud didn\\u2019t avoid email the entire month.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Once, he needed to go into his Asana account to check on an issue affecting the company\\u2019s customers.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>On another day, Renaud couldn\\u2019t resist opening his personal email to retrieve a $A106.50 rebate on some tires that he bought for his car. When he clicked on an email link confirming the rebate, he was informed it would take six to eight weeks to get his money.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u201cI have learned that I don\\u2019t need to check my email all the time,\\u201d Renaud says.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>\\u00a0<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>{jumi [*3] [AP] [http:\\/\\/www.news.com.au\\/finance\\/business\\/dustin-moskovitz-founder-of-facebook-and-asana-wants-to-see-the-end-of-the-work-email\\/story-fn5lic6c-1227007716817]}<\\/p>","fulltext":"","state":1,"catid":"12","created":"2014-07-31 03:54:00","created_by":"307","created_by_alias":"","modified":"2014-12-24 04:04:12","modified_by":"307","checked_out":"307","checked_out_time":"2014-12-24 04:03:58","publish_up":"2014-12-24 03:54:56","publish_down":"0000-00-00 00:00:00","images":"{\\"image_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"float_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_intro_caption\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext\\":\\"\\",\\"float_fulltext\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext_alt\\":\\"\\",\\"image_fulltext_caption\\":\\"\\"}","urls":"{\\"urla\\":false,\\"urlatext\\":\\"\\",\\"targeta\\":\\"\\",\\"urlb\\":false,\\"urlbtext\\":\\"\\",\\"targetb\\":\\"\\",\\"urlc\\":false,\\"urlctext\\":\\"\\",\\"targetc\\":\\"\\"}","attribs":"{\\"show_title\\":\\"\\",\\"link_titles\\":\\"\\",\\"show_tags\\":\\"\\",\\"show_intro\\":\\"\\",\\"info_block_position\\":\\"\\",\\"show_category\\":\\"\\",\\"link_category\\":\\"\\",\\"show_parent_category\\":\\"\\",\\"link_parent_category\\":\\"\\",\\"show_author\\":\\"\\",\\"link_author\\":\\"\\",\\"show_create_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_modify_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_publish_date\\":\\"\\",\\"show_item_navigation\\":\\"\\",\\"show_icons\\":\\"\\",\\"show_print_icon\\":\\"\\",\\"show_email_icon\\":\\"\\",\\"show_vote\\":\\"\\",\\"show_hits\\":\\"\\",\\"show_noauth\\":\\"\\",\\"urls_position\\":\\"\\",\\"alternative_readmore\\":\\"\\",\\"article_layout\\":\\"\\",\\"show_publishing_options\\":\\"\\",\\"show_article_options\\":\\"\\",\\"show_urls_images_backend\\":\\"\\",\\"show_urls_images_frontend\\":\\"\\"}","version":3,"ordering":"3","metakey":"","metadesc":"","access":"1","hits":"0","metadata":"{\\"robots\\":\\"\\",\\"author\\":\\"\\",\\"rights\\":\\"\\",\\"xreference\\":\\"\\"}","featured":"0","language":"*","xreference":""}', 0);
